"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456234","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-08","<p>The 2014 Government Spaceplane Review provided the groundwork for enabling spaceplane operations from the UK, including identifying key criteria for locating a UK spaceport, and identifying potential locations based on these. The Government tested the conclusions of this review through consultation and published its response in March 2015. This confirmed Campbeltown, Glasgow Prestwick and Stornoway in Scotland, Llanbedr Airfield in Wales and Newquay in England as potential spaceport locations.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on the Spaceplane review and the Government consultation can be found at https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/spaceport-locations-and-criteria</p><p> </p><p>Commercial spaceflight is a complex, international, and evolving market. The Government is considering a range of options on next steps that would best deliver our ambition of a spaceport, and the supporting regulatory environment for spaceflight, within this Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is in discussion with the US Government on ITAR-related issues. However, ITAR applications are not a factor at this stage for potential spaceport locations but may become so if a US spaceplane operator seeks to operate from the UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","28858 ; 28859 ; 28860","2016-03-08T17:17:41.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456234/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456234/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","Space Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the Government plans to issue requirements for the second round of consideration of locations for a UK spaceport.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","28861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456235","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-04","<p>The Department provides a wide range of information about the UK road network, including traffic counts for all major roads. However it does not plan to provide any information specifically on the proposed sale of the M6 Toll Road.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-04T14:23:39.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456235/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456235/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","M6: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what information his Department plans to provide to (a) the public and (b) potential investors on the proposed sale of the M6 Toll Road.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","28864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456236","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The latest cost estimates for road projects in the South West of England included in the Government's Roads Investment Strategy (RIS) for 2015-20 are below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>M49 Avonmouth Junction</strong></p></td><td><p>£37.3m - £53.6m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>A303 Sparkford to Ilchester Dualling</strong></p></td><td><p>£104.6m - £142.2m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>A358 Taunton to Southfields</strong></p></td><td><p>£351m - £517m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>M5 Junction 23</strong></p></td><td><p>less than £25m*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>A30 Chiverton Cross to Carland Cross</strong></p></td><td><p>£100m – £250m*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>A303 Amesbury to Berwick Down</strong></p></td><td><p>£864m - £1321m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>A417 Missing Link</strong></p></td><td><p>£250m - £500m *</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>A30 Temple to Higher Carblake</strong></p></td><td><p>scheme cost £56.5m. Highways England contribution = £46.5m.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>* cost as provided in RIS Investment Plan</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Updated range estimates have been prepared for some schemes since the cost categories provided in the RIS in December 2014. As schemes are developed further, they will all have their estimates updated.</p><p>I note in particular that historic attempts to improve the A303 were shelved by the previous Labour Government; we are determined to finally deliver the connectivity the south west deserves.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-03T14:33:03.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456236/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456236/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","Roads: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the latest estimated costs or final costs are for each of the road projects referred to in the Government's announcement entitled Major Roads Investment in the South West, published on 1 December 2014.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","28913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456237","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-08","<p>Since 2010, when the Maritime and Coastguard Agency has determined applications for consent, three Oil Transfer Licence applications have required appropriate assessments to be undertaken in relation to European Sites.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-08T09:46:04.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456237/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456237/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","Maritime and Coastguard Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many applications for consent determined by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency have required appropriate assessment of their effect on European wildlife sites since 2010.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","28872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456238","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-08","<p>Since 2010, when the Maritime and Coastguard Agency has determined applications for consent, three Oil Transfer Licence applications have required environmental impact assessments.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-08T09:53:41.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456238/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456238/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","Maritime and Coastguard Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many applications for consent determined by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency have required environmental impact assessment since 2010.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","28873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456239","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-08","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) is committed to reducing waiting times at Bristol, Chippenham, Trowbridge and Westbury and all other testing sites, and maintaining them at a lower level than currently seen across the UK, this is a priority for DVSA.</p><p /> <p>DVSA has run several recruitment campaigns during 2015, and continues to do so in 2016. However, due to the critical roles a driving examiner has to play in road safety, the process to recruit the right people<br>does take time. As a result of the campaigns, 139 new examiners have started work with DVSA and it has made offers of employment to another 115 people, who are currently undertaking training or waiting to attend it.</p><p> </p><p /><p /> <p> </p><p /><p />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-08T17:10:05.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456239/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456239/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","Driving Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to improve waiting times at driving test centres in (a) Bristol, (b) Chippenham, (c) Trowbridge and (d) Westbury.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","28812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456240","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>We are continuing to make progress towards announcing the decision on the scheme. You will appreciate the issues raised by the case have required very careful consideration. We are however mindful of the importance in resolving the uncertainty for Leeds as soon as possible and we hope to be in a position to announce our conclusions shortly.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-03T14:25:37.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456240/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456240/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","Trolleybuses: Leeds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects to reach a decision on the Leeds New Generation Transport Trolley Bus scheme.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","28852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456241","Department for Transport","true","2016-03-03","<p>The Department for Transport (DfT) funds the Environmental, Research and Consultancy Department of the CAA for work on aviation noise.</p><p> </p><p>Over the last 5 financial years the funding provided by the DfT was as follows</p><p> </p><p>2011/12 £725 460</p><p>2012/13 £760 087</p><p>2013/14 £694 712</p><p>2014/15 £613 267</p><p><del class="ministerial">£</del>2015/16 £712<ins class="ministerial">000</ins><del class="ministerial">k</del> (forecast for year end)</p><p> </p><p>Over these 5 years the funding has been used to:</p><ul><li>provide annual noise contours for Heathrow, Gatwick and Stansted;</li><li>Maintain the ANCON noise model which is used to estimate noise exposure;</li><li>Technical support to DFT’s Aircraft Noise Management Advisory Committee;</li><li>Evidence to support policy consultations including the night flying restrictions at Heathrow, Gatwick and Stansted;</li><li>Evidence and support to DfT in negotiating noise and emission standards for aircraft within the International Civil Aviation Organisation;</li><li>Monitoring relevant research in the field of health and annoyance impacts of aviation noise.</li></ul><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-03T14:40:10.417Z","2016-03-03T17:02:40.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456241/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456241/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456241/answer/previousversion/48883","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","Aviation: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what (a) projects and (b) funding was allocated to the Civil Aviation Authority for research on noise trunks in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","28994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456242","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-08","<p>The activities for which the Maritime and Coastguard Agency has the delegated authority to consent/refuse are for Oil Transfer Licences within UK ports and harbours and for Ship-to-Ship Transfers within the designated Southwold area off the Suffolk coast.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-08T11:34:26.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456242/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456242/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456242/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","Maritime and Coastguard Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for which activities consent is determined by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","29037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456243","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) plans to maintain its funding obligations in relation to Wrexham Driving Test Centre.</p><blockquote><p><p></blockquote>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-03T15:42:17.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456243/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456243/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456243/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","Driving Tests: Wrexham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department plans to maintain funding for a Driving Test Centre in Wrexham.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","29028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456244","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>There are four members of Department for Transport staff seconded to the South East Flexible Ticketing programme's central delivery team and one member of staff from the Association of Train Operating Companies.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-03T14:50:28.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456244/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456244/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456244/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many members of staff are currently working in the South East Flexible Ticketing programme's central delivery team from (a) his Department and (b) the Association of Train Operating Companies.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","29038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456245","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The South East Flexible Ticketing Programme’s Strategic Business Case was approved by the Rail Investment Board on 24<sup>th</sup> June 2014 and subsequently confirmed by Her Majesty’s Treasury on 22<sup>nd</sup> July that same year. The release of this document into the public domain could prejudice current policy making so it will not be placed into the Library at this stage.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-03T14:54:17.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456245/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456245/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456245/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department's South East Flexible Ticketing programme's Strategic Business Case was completed; and if he will place a copy of that document in the Library.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","29039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456246","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The information held by the Department on season tickets sales is derived from the rail industry’s central revenue and ticketing database. The Department is given access to this database for internal use only under licence by the Association of Train Operators (ATOC) who manage the database on behalf of the operators. This licence is subject to a number of conditions which restrict the Department from releasing information that has been derived from the revenue and ticketing data. ATOC’s contact details can be found on their website <a href="http://www.atoc.org/contact-us/" target="_blank">http://www.atoc.org/contact-us/</a>.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-03T15:37:25.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456246/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456246/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456246/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","Railways: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 26 February 2016 to Question 27898, whether the Association of Train Operating Companies objected to his Department releasing the average season ticket price.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","29041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456247","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-03","<p>The South East Flexible Ticketing Programme Definition Documents were last updated in June 2015. Some of these documents contain commercially sensitive information. The release of the documents could also prejudice current policy making, so they will not be placed into the Library at this stage.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-03T14:59:39.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456247/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456247/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456247/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-29","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department's South East Flexible Ticketing Programme Definition Document was last updated; and if he will place a copy of the latest version of that document in the Library.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","29040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456248","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-07","<p>The information requested is not collected or held centrally for this question as our approach is to role model best practice and encourage employers to adopt this practice.</p><p>A range of organisations from across the public and private sector, together responsible for employing 1.8 million people in the UK, have ​signed up to the pledge to operate recruitment on ‘name blind’ basis to address discrimination.</p><p>In October a number of organisations from across the public and private sector attended a roundtable at Downing Street ​to discuss this issue. <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-time-to-end-discrimination-and-finish-the-fight-for-real-equality" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-time-to-end-discrimination-and-finish-the-fight-for-real-equality</a></p><p>The Civil Service has adopted this as their default position for all external recruitment, including for graduate​s.​Other graduate recruiters who have committed to or are already delivering name-blind applications for all graduate and apprenticeship level roles include ​KPMG, HSBC, Deloitte, Virgin Money, BBC, NHS, learn-direct​​, teach first and local government.​</p><p>We are continuing to encourage this practice across the public sector and beyond.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-07T08:53:06.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456248/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456248/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456248/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456248/answer/previousversion/49000","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-29","Graduates: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Prime Minister's comments on equality in the Guardian newspaper on 26 October 2015, how many graduate employers the Government approached to ask them to pledge to anonymise job applications; how many such requests were (a) accepted and (b) rejected; and which graduate employers (i) accepted and (ii) rejected those offers.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","29029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456249","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-08","<p>A review of how transgender people – both adults and under-18s – are dealt with by prison and probation services is currently being conducted by the Ministry of Justice. This review includes those who identify as intersex. The findings and recommendations of this review will inform the review of the youth justice system which will report in July.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-03-08T11:49:34.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456249/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456249/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456249/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-29","Intersex: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will take steps to ensure that young intersex people are included in the Government's review of youth justice.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","28885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456250","Women and Equalities","false","2016-03-08","<p>Information on the proportion of girls who took A level physics in state-funded schools in 2014/15 is published as part of the “A level and other level 3 results: 2014 to 2015 (revised)” statistical first release.[1] In independent schools[2] 9.3% of girls took A level physics in 2014/15.</p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/a-level-and-other-level-3-results-2014-to-2015-revised" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/a-level-and-other-level-3-results-2014-to-2015-revised</a> (Document titled: Maths and science tables; Tab titled: Table 18)</p><p>[2] Excludes independent special schools and non-maintained special schools.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-08T13:51:24.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456250/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456250/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456250/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-02-29","Physics: GCE A-level","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what proportion of girls in (a) state and (b) private schools took physics A-level in 2015.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","28889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456251","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-08","<p>The DWP recognises the position of parents who have children with mental health problems and supports them through the award of Disability Living Allowance where the relevant entitlement conditions are met. As a Department we have multiple channels to ensure our customers are provided with the best possible information about their entitlement to benefits. These include:</p><p> </p><p><strong>Public Information</strong></p><p>The Department provides information on benefits, including Disability Living Allowance (DLA), in a range of formats on www.gov.uk. This includes information relating to DLA for children and includes links to benefit eligibility calculators that will signpost the user to further information about DLA for children.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Customer Facing Staff</strong></p><p>Learning and development for our customer facing/telephony staff raises awareness around the different needs of vulnerable customers. We also have a portal that all staff can access to appropriately signpost support available.</p><p> </p><p>Staff would actively consider this in their dealings with parents of disabled children, offering information on claiming Disability Living Allowance if appropriate.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Partnership Working</strong></p><p>The Department also works with a range of organisations that provide information and advice on claiming DLA for children, such as Disability Rights UK, Contact a Family, Young Minds, NetMums and Carers UK. Our policy teams ensure that national partner organisations are kept informed about policy changes.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Visiting</strong></p><p>Where a family is identified as needing a visit, our visiting officers typically complete holistic benefit checks which would include DLA considerations for any child.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-03-08T15:15:16.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456251/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456251/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456251/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-29","Disability Living Allowance: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that the parents of children with mental health problems are aware that their child may be eligible to claim disability living allowance.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","28800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456252","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-03","<p>Universal Credit takes earnings into account in a manner that is fair and simple to understand. Earnings are taken into account in the assessment period in which they are received and the Universal Credit award adjusted accordingly. We have no plans to change this policy.</p><p> </p><p>Claimants have access to help and support from the first day they make a claim to Universal Credit, regardless of when earnings are received.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-03-03T15:28:37.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456252/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456252/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456252/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-29","Universal Credit: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will review entitlement to universal credit of people whose wages are paid two weeks in arrears after their temporary employment contract has ended.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","29044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456253","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-03","<p>DWP officials are continuing to work with the Ministry of Justice to assess the potential impact of the proposed changes. The government will consult on these measures which will be accompanied by an impact assessment that will cover claims for compensation which are recoverable under the Social Security (Recovery of Benefits) Act 1997.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-03-03T13:43:44.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456253/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456253/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456253/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-29","Social Security Benefits: Personal Injury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the answer of 14 January 2016 to Question 21498, on social security benefits: personal injury, whether the estimated effect of the proposed changes on social security recoupment from injuries other than whiplash are likely to be caught by the changes.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","28992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456576","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-11","<p>Digital is one of the fastest-growing and most innovative sectors. It currently supports 1.4 million jobs in the UK and according to the DCMS Digital Sector Economic Estimates, published in January 2016, contributed £118.3 billion to the UK economy in 2014 - up 7.2% on the previous year - accounting for 7.3% of the UK economy. Total UK digital exports came to £43 billion in 2013, equalling 8.2 per cent of all UK exports (goods and services).</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-11T17:09:25.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456576/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456576/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456576/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-29","Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the value to the economy of the technology sector.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","903867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456822","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-03","<p>Children and Young People are at the centre of our First World War Centenary Commemorations. We want to see young people across the country learning about the war.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-03-03T14:53:50.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456822/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456822/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-29","World War I: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure the greatest possible engagement by children and young people in the commemoration of the First World War.","false","Biography information for Graham Evans","Weaver Vale","Graham Evans","903870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457185","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-03","<p>In June 2015 I wrote to the Chairs of the BBC Trust and Ofcom on this subject. Their replies set out their plans. The Trust has since consulted on and published guidelines for covering the referendum.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-03T18:00:22.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457185/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457185/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-29","BBC: Political Impartiality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to ensure that the BBC upholds its obligations under the charter relating to impartiality during the EU referendum campaign.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","903872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457186","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-03","<p>This Government will continue to invest in the great towns and cities of the North to support growth and increase engagement in the arts through our capital funding and investment by the Arts Council. We will support innovative exciting arts and culture projects such as the Factory in Manchester and the Great Exhibition which will celebrate the fantastic culture of the North.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-03T18:00:50.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457186/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457186/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-29","Arts: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans the Government has to support the Northern Powerhouse through funding for the arts.","false","Biography information for Chris Green","Bolton West","Chris Green","903873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457187","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-03","<p>Our aim is to introduce new funding arrangements for British racing by April 2017.</p><p> </p><p>We will create a level playing field for British based and offshore gambling operators, and ensure a fair return from all bookmakers to racing, which has been lost simply because of the shift to remote offshore betting.</p><p> </p><p>Racing will be responsible for making decisions on spending the new fund. We will make a further announcement shortly.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-03-03T14:52:49.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457187/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457187/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-29","Horse Racing: Betting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress he has made on replacing the current horserace betting levy.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","903874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457188","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-03","<p>It is a matter for MG Alba how it distributes funding across it services. The previous government provided two one-off grants to MG ALBA, which we understand was put into developing the drama series Bannan.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-03T17:59:19.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457188/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457188/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-29","Digital Broadcasting: Scots Gaelic Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on Scottish sport of changes to the funding of BBC Alba.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","903869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457189","House of Commons Commission","false","2016-03-03","<p>Members decided not to allow televised coverage of the House for satirical purposes as part of the broadcasting arrangements which came into place in 1989. This followed recommendations made by the Select Committee on Televising of Proceedings of the House (<em><a href="https://4l32cg.dm2302.livefilestore.com/y3mCcGtmxNmToTk66kML7D-mt3-XG-FtGiyMmOLALgp_nvg0Re1QX8R_cp9ZSetfXuDq2Byq-cTSuKedsdihya86s9M30VpDwUmxIt5E8RpCpguNX_WAFqYhibSw-gtFm923F-GR6rD1tDXR4MtNWVQDQ/Broadcasting%20Committee%20First%20Report%2089-89%20HC%20141-I.pdf?psid=1" target="_blank">First Report 1988–89, HC 141-I</a>, para 50</em>).</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2016-03-03T12:20:03.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457189/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457189/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2016-02-29","House of Commons: Broadcasting Programmes","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, what the Commission's policy is on the use of House broadcast footage in programmes of a satirical nature.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","903894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455693","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-10","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-10T16:54:44.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455693/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455693/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455693/answer/previousversion/48668","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-26","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the Prime Minister's Oral Statement of 22 February 2016, Official Report, column 35, on the European Council, whether his Department is undertaking planning in the eventuality of a majority leave vote in the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","28707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455694","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Government’s believes that the best way to meet the UK’s steel needs over the next twelve months and five years is to ensure a viable future for the steel industry in Britain, as well as to work for fair and open global steel markets. To this end we have taken action on the five short-term asks of the steel industry, for example on unfairly-traded imports, energy costs, procurement, and emissions regulations.</p><p> </p><p>A new Steel Council will provide a forum for industry, unions and government to consider how to improve the competitive position of the UK steel sector in the longer term. We will continue to work actively with partners in this sector, local taskforces and the EU and International Community to support our steel industry.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-02T16:23:07.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455694/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455694/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-26","Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if his Department will produce a strategy on how the UK's steel requirements will be met over the next (a) 12 months and (b) five years.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","28734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455695","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-02","<p>Her Majesty’s Government takes its export responsibilities very seriously and operates one of the most robust arms export control regimes in the world.</p><p> </p><p>All exports of arms and controlled military goods are assessed on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria, taking account of all relevant factors at the time of the application. This includes the UK’s obligations under Council Common Position 2008/944/CFSP.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is satisfied that we are not in breach of our international obligations, including under the Council Common Position 2008/944/CFSP. A licence will not be issued, to Saudi Arabia or any other destination, if to do so would be inconsistent with any provision of the mandatory UK Licensing Criteria.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-02T17:24:04.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455695/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455695/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-26","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the UK's policy is on the resolution passed by the European Parliament in February 2016 in favour of an embargo on the sale of arms to Saudi Arabia.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","28765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455696","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-07","<p>No representations have been received on the legal advice commissioned by Amnesty International and Saferworld.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-07T14:13:31.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455696/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455696/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-26","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2016 to Question 27077, on arms trade: Saudi Arabia, what representations he has received on that legal advice.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","28775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455697","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-07","<p>The Crown Commercial Service only collects regional spend data for direct spend with small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs), so the following figures, which are taken from the Governments Spend Analytical tool, Bravo, do not incorporate spend through the supply chain.</p><p>Direct spend with SMEs of £205,978,657.91 was reported in 2014-15 for the North West of England.</p><p>During the same period, the following amounts were reported as going to small businesses in the requested locations:</p><p>OL1 - £2,706,290.86</p><p>OL2 - £18,611.30</p><p>OL3 - £54,984.10</p><p>OL4 - £66,325.40</p><p>OL8 - £83,737.93</p><p>OL9 - £566,399.25</p><p>M35 - £76,074.91</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","28726","2016-03-07T13:04:46.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455697/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455697/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-26","Small Businesses: Oldham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the figures on central government spend with small and medium-sized enterprises, published on 5 December 2015, how much of the £12.1 billion was spent in 2014-15 with businesses located in the OL1, OL2, OL3, OL4, OL8, OL9 and M35 postcode areas.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","28763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455698","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-07","<p>The Crown Commercial Service only collects regional spend data for direct spend with small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs), so the following figures, which are taken from the Governments Spend Analytical tool, Bravo, do not incorporate spend through the supply chain.</p><p>Direct spend with SMEs of £205,978,657.91 was reported in 2014-15 for the North West of England.</p><p>During the same period, the following amounts were reported as going to small businesses in the requested locations:</p><p>OL1 - £2,706,290.86</p><p>OL2 - £18,611.30</p><p>OL3 - £54,984.10</p><p>OL4 - £66,325.40</p><p>OL8 - £83,737.93</p><p>OL9 - £566,399.25</p><p>M35 - £76,074.91</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","28763","2016-03-07T13:04:46.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455698/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455698/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-26","Small Businesses: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much central government expenditure on small and medium-sized enterprises in 2014-15 was spent in the North West.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","28726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455699","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-02","<p>I can confirm that Airbnb is not currently an FCA-authorised firm. However, it is not for the Government to comment on the regulatory status of individual firms. It is for the FCA to decide whether a firm should be brought into regulation, based on a detailed assessment of that firm’s activities, and with reference to the regulations that the FCA is responsible for enforcing. It is for firms to review their own business operations to see whether they are carrying out regulated activities.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-02T16:48:34.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455699/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455699/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-26","Airbnb: Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of whether payments to AirBnB constitute remittances for the purposes of financial regulation.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","28730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455700","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-02","<p>The government will need to consider the proposals from both Transport for the North and the National Infrastructure Commission before taking any funding decisions. The Government looks forward to the publication of both reports in the coming weeks.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-02T17:59:40.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455700/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455700/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-26","Transport: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to provide additional funding for projects identified by the forthcoming Northern Transport Strategy.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","28724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455701","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-07","<p>The government continues to keep all taxes under review and decisions on tax policy are made as part of the Budget process.</p><p> </p><p>The government is committed to supporting the beer industry. The tax on a typical pint of beer was cut by a penny at March Budget 2015, building on the duty cuts at Budget 2014 and Budget 2013.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-03-07T11:09:30.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455701/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455701/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-26","Beer: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has for the future level of beer duty.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","28750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455702","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-03","<p>The Government has committed to work with local authorities, homelessness organisations and across government departments to consider options, including legislation, to prevent more households becoming homeless. We will look to learn from other countries who have innovated in the way they deal with homelessness.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-03-03T10:58:32.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455702/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455702/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-26","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make a comparative assessment of the effectiveness of the powers available to the devolved administrations and local authorities in England to tackle homelessness.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","28753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455703","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-03","<p>The legal definition of homelessness is set out in Section 175 of the Housing Act 1996. Broadly speaking, somebody is statutorily homeless if they do not have accommodation that they have a legal right to occupy, which is accessible and physically available to them (and their household) and which it would be reasonable for them to continue to live in. It would not be reasonable for someone to continue to live in their home, for example, if that was likely to lead to violence against them (or a member of their family).</p><p><br></p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-03-03T10:59:32.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455703/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455703/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-26","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his Department's definition is of a homeless person.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","28754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455704","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-02","<p>The initial procurement exercise in 2006 inviting bids to run a custodial tenancy deposit scheme and up to three insurance tenancy deposit schemes received four bids. Two of the companies were small or medium sized businesses.</p><p>In 2015, the re-procurement exercise for a new custodial tenancy scheme also received four bids. Three of the companies were small or medium sized businesses.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-02T17:04:20.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455704/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455704/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-26","Tenancy Deposit Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many companies responded to his Department's invitation to tender for the protection of tenancy deposit scheme; and how many of those companies were small or medium-sized businesses.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","28729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455705","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-03","<p>For local elections the last date by which the notice of election must be published is the 25<sup>th</sup> working day before the day of election.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-03-03T16:50:11.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455705/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455705/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-26","Mayors: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his assessment is of the latest date on which the process of organising an election in May 2017 for a Regional Mayor in the north east of England can begin.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","28738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455706","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-03","<p>Our intention is that secondary legislation to enable the election of a mayor for the North East Combined Authority in May 2017 will be made by November 2016.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-03-03T16:50:59.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455706/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455706/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-26","Mayors: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his Department's timetable is for the legislative process for election of a Regional Mayor in the north east of England.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","28739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455707","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-03","<p>I am satisfied that the potential risk of successful legal proceedings against the Department in relation to implementation of EU Directive 41/2003 is low, because it has been properly implemented in respect of the local government pension scheme.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-03-03T16:51:44.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455707/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455707/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-26","Local Government: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential risk of legal proceedings against his Department as a result of non-implementation of EU Directive 41/2003 on Institutions for Occupational Retirement Provision.","true","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","28740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455708","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-14","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-14T16:28:53.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455708/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455708/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-26","Department for Communities and Local Government: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Prime Minister's Oral Statement of 22 February 2016, Official Report, column 35, on the European Council, whether his Department is undertaking planning in the eventuality of a majority leave vote in the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","28697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455709","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-03","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-03T17:10:25.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455709/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455709/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-26","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Prime Minister's Oral Statement of 22 February 2016, Official Report, column 35, on the European Council, whether his Department is undertaking planning in the eventuality of a majority leave vote in the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","28698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455710","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-02","<p>Broadcasters are subject to the provisions of the Equality Act 2010 which legally protects disabled people from discrimination in the delivery of services and in wider society. This government is actively encouraging the industry to be proactive in increasing diversity on and off screen - including by increasing the representation of disabled people. Ed Vaizey hosted a conference in January that raised the wider issue of lack of representation of disabled people in the creative industries.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-02T15:51:08.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455710/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455710/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-26","Broadcasting Programmes: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the extent to which the policies of broadcasters recruiting members of the public for quiz or game shows or similar programmes discriminate against people with disabilities.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","28741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455711","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-02","<p>Hollywood studio films refer to films produced and distributed by a major studio based in the United States. No British Film Institute (BFI) funding has been awarded to any Hollywood studio film since the BFI became a Lottery distributor in 2011.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-02T11:27:24.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455711/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455711/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-26","British Film Institute","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what information his Department holds on the proportion of British Film Institute funding that was allocated to Hollywood studio films in the latest period for which figures are available; and what definition of Hollywood studio films is used in this context.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","28728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455712","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-02","<p>At the February European Council the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February 2016, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-03-02T17:29:11.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455712/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455712/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-26","Ministry of Defence: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Prime Minister's Oral Statement of 22 February 2016, Official Report, column 35, on the European Council, whether his Department is undertaking planning in the eventuality of a majority leave vote in the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","28708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455713","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-02","<p>There were 2 Category (Cat.) (A) and 1 Cat. (B) Incident(s) in the Scottish Flight Information Region/Upper Information Region (Scottish FIR/UIR) and 1 Cat (A) and 4 Cat. (B) incidents in the London FIR/UIR.</p><p> </p><p>The table below outlines the type of military aircraft involved in each incident in both regions since 2010.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Airprox No</p></td><td><p>Date</p></td><td><p>Risk</p></td><td><p>Location</p></td><td><p>Aircraft Type</p></td><td><p>Country of origin</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012060</p></td><td><p>27/04/2012</p></td><td><p>A</p></td><td><p>LONDON FIR</p></td><td><p>KC135 STRATOTANKER</p></td><td><p>USA</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015009</p></td><td><p>04/02/2015</p></td><td><p>B</p></td><td><p>LONDON FIR</p></td><td><p>F15 EAGLE</p></td><td><p>USA</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013037</p></td><td><p>16/05/2013</p></td><td><p>B</p></td><td><p>LONDON FIR</p></td><td><p>F15 EAGLE</p></td><td><p>USA</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015111</p></td><td><p>14/07/2015</p></td><td><p>B</p></td><td><p>LONDON FIR</p></td><td><p>C5 GALAXY</p></td><td><p>USA</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015123</p></td><td><p>30/07/2015</p></td><td><p>B</p></td><td><p>LONDON FIR</p></td><td><p>F15 EAGLE</p></td><td><p>USA</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012057</p></td><td><p>24/04/2012</p></td><td><p>A</p></td><td><p>SCOTTISH FIR</p></td><td><p>C130 HERCULES</p></td><td><p>USA</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010163</p></td><td><p>13/10/2010</p></td><td><p>A</p></td><td><p>SCOTTISH FIR</p></td><td><p>SAAB JAS39 GRIPEN</p></td><td><p>Not recorded</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013149</p></td><td><p>10/10/2013</p></td><td><p>B</p></td><td><p>SCOTTISH FIR</p></td><td><p>MIRAGE 2000</p></td><td><p>France</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The associated Airprox reports can be found on the UK Airprox board website (<a href="http://www.airproxboard.org.uk" target="_blank">www.airproxboard.org.uk</a>) under 'Reports and Analysis'.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-02T16:42:38.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455713/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455713/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-26","Military Aircraft: Air Misses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many International Civil Aviation Organisation category (a) A and (b) B Airprox incidents there were in the (i) Scottish Flight Information Region/Upper Information Region and (ii) London Flight Information Region/Upper Information Region involved foreign military aircraft in each year since 2010; and in each of those incidents what the (A) type of foreign military aircraft involved and (B) country of origin was.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","28773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455714","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-02","<p>Since 2010 there have been no Significant Occurrence Notifications (SONs) involving other nations' military aircraft in the Scottish Flight Information Region/Upper Information Region. Four SONs have been raised relating to other nations' aircraft operating in the London Flight Information Region/Upper Information Region since 2010, all of which were notified to Director General Defence Safety Authority. These are detailed below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date of SON issue/ Event occurrence</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Aircraft Type</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Country of Origin</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Occurrence Type</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>7 January 2014</p></td><td><p>HH-60G Pave Hawk</p></td><td><p>USA</p></td><td><p>Crash</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>8 October 2014</p></td><td><p>F-15 Eagle</p></td><td><p>USA</p></td><td><p>Crash</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>13 October 2015</p></td><td><p>Sea King CH-124A Mk3</p></td><td><p>Canada</p></td><td><p>Maintenance accident</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>21 October 2015</p></td><td><p>F/A-18C Hornet</p></td><td><p>USA</p></td><td><p>Crash</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-03-02T16:16:05.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455714/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455714/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-26","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many Significant Occurrence Notifications the Director of General Defence Safety Authority has been notified of which involved other nations' military aircraft operating in the (a) Scottish Flight Information Region/Upper Information Region and (b) London Flight Information Region/Upper Information Region in each year since 2010; and what the (i) type of foreign military aircraft and (ii) country of origin was in each of those occurrences.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","28774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455715","Department for Education","false","2016-03-03","<p>This Government is investing in Step Up to Social Work and Frontline, our fast-track graduate entry programmes, to attract future high-calibre graduates into social work. We aim to train over 3,000 new social workers through fast-track schemes over the Spending Review period.</p><p>The cost for the continuation of the Frontline pilot from April 2016 – end March 2019 is estimated at around £10m.</p><p>In October 2015, Government issued a tender for a national fast-track social work programme to succeed the Frontline pilot. Funds will be allocated for delivery once the contract is confirmed. Costs will vary according to actual numbers recruited.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-03-03T15:13:56.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455715/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455715/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-26","Social Workers: Graduates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Prime Minister's announcement of 14 December 2015, We will not stand by - failing children's services will be taken over, how the Government plans to spend the £100 million to be invested in attracting more high-calibre graduates into social work.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","28764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455716","Department for Education","false","2016-03-02","<p>Music is compulsory for all children in key stages 1-3 in maintained schools. One of the requirements of the National Curriculum is that pupils are taught to play musical instruments. Schools are not permitted to charge for teaching that is required by the National Curriculum.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is investing £75m in 2015-16 in a network of music education hubs. Music education hubs have four core roles, one of which is to ensure that every child aged 5-18 learns to play a musical instrument through whole class ensemble teaching. Data published by Arts Council England in March 2015 showed that 596,820 pupils in the academic year 2013/14 learned to play an instrument through whole class ensemble teaching. This teaching is provided free for pupils.</p><p>The data is available here: <a href="http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/media/uploads/Music_Education_Hubs_2014_Report_final_March_2015.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/media/uploads/Music_Education_Hubs_2014_Report_final_March_2015.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Arts Council England will publish data for the 2014-15 academic year in due course. This will include more extensive data on the number of pupils who have singing or instrumental lessons.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-02T17:31:36.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455716/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455716/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-26","Schools: Musical Instruments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the number of state (a) primary and (b) secondary students who are learning a musical instrument; and how many such students are learning that musical instrument for free.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","28761"
