"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455199","Department for Education","false","2016-03-01","<p>The reformed national pay and terms and conditions arrangements allow all schools considerable flexibility over the pay of their teachers.</p><p>Staff at academies are employees of academy trusts, companies limited by guarantee with charitable status. Whilst academy trusts are classified as public sector bodies, their staff are not employees of the Crown. Academies have more control over their budgets so that they can meet their school’s needs more effectively and have the flexibility to reward the best teachers and excellent performance. These are the reasons they are not included within the statutory national pay and terms and conditions arrangements, which includes the current one per cent cap on pay increases.</p><p>Many academies have pay systems that mirror the provisions of the statutory national arrangements and many converter academy staff have ‘Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) Regulations’ rights that preserve their entitlement to the national pay and terms and conditions arrangements.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","28588","2016-03-01T16:48:35.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455199/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455199/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-25","Academies: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the exemption of academy school staff from the one per cent public sector pay rise limit.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","28585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455200","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-04","<p>The Cabinet Office does not hold the information that has been requested as separate data for cases based wholly or partially on the Human Rights Act 1998 are not recorded.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-04T14:59:58.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455200/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455200/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Cabinet Office: Human Rights Act 1998","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many civil law suits have been brought against his Department based either wholly or partially on grounds provided by the Human Rights Act 1998; how many such suits were settled out of court before a court judgment was delivered; and how much such settlements have cost the public purse since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455201","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-04","<p>As part of this Government’s transparency agenda, all Departments are required to publish monthly workforce statistics that includes overtime costs. This information is available from the Cabinet Office website at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/payroll-costs-and-non-consolidated-pay-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/payroll-costs-and-non-consolidated-pay-data</a></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-04T13:52:19.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455201/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455201/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Cabinet Office: Overtime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much his Department has paid to staff in overtime in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455202","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-04","<p>Since December 2012 a policy of 'digital by default' has been applied to all Cabinet Office publications. All publications and consultations are published via <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a></p><p>All publications are searchable by date and displayed by title.</p><p>A search of <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> shows 1110 publications in total since 1st August 2012; this includes 33 consultations.</p><p>For circulars, including newsletters and group emails, an accurate answer could only be provided at disproportionate costs.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-04T13:51:26.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455202/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455202/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Cabinet Office: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many (a) publications, (b) consultation documents and (c) circulars his Department has issued since August 2012; and what the title was of each such publication, consultation document or circular.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455203","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-04","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-04T13:52:00.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455203/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455203/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Cabinet Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many consultants' contracts were terminated early in each of the last six years for which figures are available; and what the cost of each such termination was in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455204","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-07","<p>All staff and contractors based in Downing Street are paid at least the London Living Wage.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-07T13:08:08.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455204/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455204/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Prime Minister: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the rate of pay is for cleaners in 10 Downing Street.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","28562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455205","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-04","<p>In the last 12 months the Cabinet Office has spent £55,786 on legal costs relating to cases that were heard at employment tribunals.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-04T13:51:04.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455205/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455205/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Cabinet Office: Employment Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much his Department spent from the public purse on industrial tribunals in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455206","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-07","<p>The following platforms have been commissioned or built to improve the delivery of Government services:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Departments</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Name</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMRC Home Office</p></td><td><p><strong>One Government at the Border</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ministry of Justice Home Office</p></td><td><p><strong>Digital Justice</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GDS</p></td><td><p><strong>GOV.UK Verify</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GDS</p></td><td><p><a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank"><strong>GOV.UK</strong></a></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GDS</p></td><td><p><strong>GOV.UK Pay</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GDS</p></td><td><p><strong>GOV.UK Notify</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GDS</p></td><td><p><strong>PaaS / Hosting for digital services</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DWP HMRC</p></td><td><p><strong>Check your state pension</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-07T13:03:17.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455206/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455206/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what shared platforms the Government is building or has commissioned to improve the delivery of Government services.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","28532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455207","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>Consecutive, independent evaluations have demonstrated that National Citizen Service (NCS) delivers value for money and that the cost per participant has fallen since NCS began. In 2013, the NCS Trust, an independent social enterprise, was established to manage NCS and deliver the programme. Cabinet Office is working closely with the NCS Trust to develop their plans to extend NCS to 360,000 young people per year by 2020, whilst ensuring value for money for the taxpayer.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-03-01T11:09:08.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455207/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455207/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how he plans to reduce the cost per participant of the National Citizen Service.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","28527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455208","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Cabinet Office promotes a number of cross Government talent schemes to Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic (BAME) and disabled staff, to accelerate their promotion to Senior Civil Service roles. This includes Civil Service wide talent schemes such the Future Leaders Scheme (aimed at G6&amp;7 staff) and the Senior Leaders Scheme (aimed at SCS Pay Band 1). Additionally, it promotes development schemes aimed specifically at BAME and disabled staff including the Accelerate talent programme (for SCS) and the Positive Action Pathway (for staff below SCS).</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","28477","2016-03-02T10:56:07.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455208/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455208/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455208/answer/previousversion/48401","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Cabinet Office: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department is taking to improve Black and minority ethnic representation in the Senior Civil Service his Department.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","28482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455209","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>At 31 January 2016, the Private Office Group in my department employed no officials on temporary contracts.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-02T10:56:44.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455209/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455209/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455209/answer/previousversion/48400","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Ministers' Private Offices: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many officials in the private offices group are employed on temporary contracts.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","28483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455210","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-03-02T17:52:27.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455210/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455210/answer","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455210/answer/previousversion/48403","Biography information for John Penrose","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Cabinet Office: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Prime Minister's Oral Statement of 22 February 2016, Official Report, column 35, on the European Council, whether his Department is undertaking planning in the eventuality of a majority leave vote in the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","28505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455211","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-04","<p>The Cabinet Office routinely purchases software components to facilitate business operations and has purchased a number of software components, such as desktop software, document management systems, business applications and software as service components. Details of transactions are listed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/cabinet-office-spend-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/cabinet-office-spend-data</a></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-04T13:51:42.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455211/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455211/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Cabinet Office: Computer Software","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what investment his Department has made in software components in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","28515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455212","Cabinet Office","true","2016-03-04","<p><del class="ministerial">Promoting diversity in the Senior Civil Service is a ministerial responsibility of the Minister for the Cabinet Office. I have had frequent such meetings, and details of Ministers' meetings with external organisations are published routinely and can be found on www. Gov.UK.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">As part of this Government’s transparency agenda, twice a year all Departments are required to publish an organogram and structure charts that contain information about the roles performed by staff. The latest Cabinet Office organogram is available at <a href="https://data.gov.uk/organogram/cabinet-office" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/organogram/cabinet-office</a> and the latest structure charts may be downloaded at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/cabinet-office-structure-charts" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/cabinet-office-structure-charts</a>.</ins></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-04T13:50:32.96Z","2016-03-07T16:23:22.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455212/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455212/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455212/answer/previousversion/49154","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Cabinet Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many officials in his Department are responsible for coordinating and developing international policy across Government.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","28516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455213","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-04","<p>The Government is committed to increasing the diversity of public appointments and​ has an​ aspiration that 50% of new public appointees should be women. We are making ​good ​progress, with 44% of new appointments made to women in 2014-2015 and a higher proportion of all public appointments (new appointments and reappointments) went to women last year than at any other point previously recorded.</p><p>The Centre for Public Appointments in the Cabinet Office supports departments on all issues relating to the diversity of public appointments. Steps we are taking to increase diversity include streamlining the application process​, placing an emphasis on ability over previous experience,​ and increasing awareness of opportunities by using a central website, social media.</p><p>I hosted an event in February for a variety of diversity networks to encourage people from underrepresented groups to apply for Public Appointments and to advertise them in their own networks. The Cabinet Office is also represented at events run by diversity networks to raise awareness of the opportunities available.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-04T13:50:16.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455213/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455213/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Public Appointments: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he has taken to increase the number of public appointments of women in the last three months.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","28517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455214","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-04","<p>The Government is committed to increasing the diversity of public appointments. The Centre for Public Appointments in the Cabinet Office supports departments on all issues relating to the diversity of public appointments. Steps we are taking to increase diversity include streamlining the application process​, placing an emphasis on ability over previous experience,​ and increasing awareness of opportunities by using a central website, social media. The Centre for Public Appointments also engages extensively with a variety of diversity networks​ and groups representing the views of ethnic minorities to raise awareness and increase the number of applications coming from BAME candidates and understand any potential issues or barriers.</p><p>I hosted an event in February for a variety of diversity networks to encourage people from underrepresented groups to apply for Public Appointments and to advertise them in their own networks. The Cabinet Office is also represented at events run by diversity networks to raise awareness of the opportunities available.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-04T13:52:37.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455214/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455214/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Public Appointments: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he has taken to increase the number of public appointments of BAME representation in the last three months.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","28518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455215","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>The grants clause announced on 6 February prevents recipients of taxpayer-funded grants from using them to lobby rather than for the purposes for which they were given.</p><p>The clause does not prevent grant recipients from meeting with ministers, responding to public consultations or giving evidence to select committees.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-02T10:55:15.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455215/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455215/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455215/answer/previousversion/48399","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Lobbying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will issue a response to EDM 1138, Anti-lobbying Clause in Government Grant Agreements.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","28436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455216","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-04","<p>On 2 February we published a report by the Bridge Group on socio-economic diversity in the Civil Service’s flagship graduate recruitment programme, the Fast Stream. This report can be accessed from the link at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/socio-economic-diversity-in-the-fast-stream-the-bridge-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/socio-economic-diversity-in-the-fast-stream-the-bridge-report</a> and my accompanying speech at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/addressing-inequality-in-the-public-sector-and-beyond-matt-hancock-speech" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/addressing-inequality-in-the-public-sector-and-beyond-matt-hancock-speech</a>&quot;</p><p>For the Fast Stream graduate programme and for the Fast Track apprenticeship scheme, we already collect information from candidates about their socio-economic background. We are working to implement the Bridge Group recommendations on the best measures of socio-economic background for these programmes, including collecting home postcode and school attended by applicants, both at age 14. Both of these new data items will be collected for recruitment to Fast Stream and Fast Track for new competitions from 2016.</p><p>We will publish our Social Mobility Strategy for the Civil Service in the Spring, in which we will set out our approach to measuring socio-economic diversity in the wider workforce.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-04T13:49:55.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455216/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455216/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Civil Servants: Social Status","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress the Government has made on determining how best to collect and track data on socio-economic background in the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","28476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455217","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-02","<p>The Cabinet Office promotes a number of cross Government talent schemes to Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic (BAME) and disabled staff, to accelerate their promotion to Senior Civil Service roles. This includes Civil Service wide talent schemes such the Future Leaders Scheme (aimed at G6&amp;7 staff) and the Senior Leaders Scheme (aimed at SCS Pay Band 1). Additionally, it promotes development schemes aimed specifically at BAME and disabled staff including the Accelerate talent programme (for SCS) and the Positive Action Pathway (for staff below SCS).</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","28482","2016-03-02T10:56:07.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455217/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455217/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Cabinet Office: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department is taking to improve the representation of employees with a disability in the Senior Civil Service in the Cabinet Office.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","28477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455218","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-07","<p>Promoting diversity in the Senior Civil Service is a ministerial responsibility of the Minister for the Cabinet Office. I have had frequent such meetings, and details of ministers' meetings with external organisations are published routinely and can be found on Gov.uk.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-07T16:41:14.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455218/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455218/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Senior Civil Servants: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many times the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster has met external organisations in the last six months to discuss improving diversity in the Senior Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","28478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455219","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-04","<p>We have completed a skills review process across different government departments in the last 3 years considering leading and managing change, programme management, digital, and commercial skills and this has given a high level indication of the areas where we need to increase capability. Our approach to learning and development includes specific focus on these areas.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-04T13:52:50.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455219/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455219/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-25","Civil Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of in which areas of the Civil Service there is a deficit in capabilities.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","28479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455220","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-03","<p><strong>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</strong></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-03T17:13:45.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455220/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455220/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Treasury: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Prime Minister's Oral Statement of 22 February 2016, Official Report, column 35, on the European Council, whether his Department is undertaking planning in the eventuality of a majority leave vote in the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","28504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455221","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-04","<p>The Government is taking forward a range of measures to tackle the problem of nuisance calls, including strengthening the regulators’ ability to take enforcement action against organisations that break the law and increasing consumer choice by consulting on making it a requirement for direct marketing callers to display their calling line identification. As part of the £3.5m package announced in budget, Government launched a competition for innovative solutions to tackle the scourge of nuisance calls - and contracts have been awarded to successful applicants, to help develop their products to launch on the open market and benefit customers right across the country. In addition, £0.5 million funding is going to the National Trading Standards Scams Team - via East Sussex County Council - to provide call blocking devices to vulnerable people nationwide and report its effects.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-04T13:17:46.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455221/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455221/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-25","Nuisance Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his plans are for the £3.5 million funding announced for tackling nuisance calls in paragraph 2.289 of the March 2015 Budget, HC 1093 of Session 2014-15; how much of this funding has been allocated to which local authorities; what information his Department holds on the number of call blockers that this funding has paid for the installation of in domestic properties; and what assessment his Department has made of the effect of that funding in the volumes of nuisance calls received and reports of such calls made.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","28507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455222","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Government is taking concerns about the Anti-Money Laundering requirements regarding Politically Exposed Persons (PEPs) seriously. While addressing corrupt PEPs is an important aspect of global efforts to tackle corruption and money laundering, it is essential that this be done proportionately. Treasury ministers have regular discussions with banks and the FCA, including on ensuring that guidance is clear and appropriate.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-01T15:39:51.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455222/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455222/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the FCA on its making guidance available to banks which are seeking to comply with money laundering rules in relation to domestic politically-exposed persons in a proportionate way; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","28484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455223","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-04","<p>The value of tax credit overpayments and tax credit recoveries in a tax year is published in HM Revenue &amp; Customs, Annual Report and Accounts, available through www.gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p>The following are hyperlinks to each of the requested years</p><p> </p><p>2010-11</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/89199/annual-report-accounts-1011.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/89199/annual-report-accounts-1011.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>2011-12</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/89198/annual-report-accounts-1112.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/89198/annual-report-accounts-1112.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>2012-13</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/210244/9549-TSO-HMRC_RA_ACCESSIBLE.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/210244/9549-TSO-HMRC_RA_ACCESSIBLE.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>2013-14</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/330670/HMRC-annual-report-2013-14.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/330670/HMRC-annual-report-2013-14.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>2014-15</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/449343/HMRC_Annual_Report_and_Accounts_2014-15__Web_accessible_version_.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/449343/HMRC_Annual_Report_and_Accounts_2014-15__Web_accessible_version_.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-03-04T11:47:46.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455223/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455223/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Welfare Tax Credits: Overpayments","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the value of tax credit overpayments has been in each financial year since 2010; and how much of that amount HM Revenue and Customs has recovered in each such year.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","28541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455224","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>This answer could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-03-01T17:47:38.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455224/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455224/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average change in tax credit awards was as a result of an increase in yearly household income above the income rise disregard in each financial year since 2006.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","28526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455225","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>As announced in the combined Autumn Statement and Spending Review, the amount by which a tax credit claimant’s income can increase within the year before their tax credit award is adjusted (the income rise disregard), will be reduced from £5,000 to £2,500. The reduction to the income rise disregard will stop one family receiving a higher tax credit award over another family with precisely the same income and the same circumstances, which makes the system fairer. The household income of families before it rises will inform how they might be effected by a reduction in the income rise disregard.</p><p> </p><p>The only people who will be affected are those who will see an income increase of more than £2,500 in-year.</p><p> </p><p>Due to the way that tax credits are calculated, the amount an award will be adjusted by – because of an increase in income – will depend upon a claimant’s individual circumstances, such as the household’s income before it rises. No one will be a cash loser because their income will have increased. As an example, for an individual with a wage of £12,000, an income increase of £2,501 would lead to an adjustment in their tax credit award of just 41 pence. An increase of less than £2,500 would see no change at all.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","28530 ; 28580","2016-03-01T17:46:37.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455225/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455225/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 5 January 2016 to Question 20332, if he will place in the Library all case studies his Department undertook for the purpose of establishing the effect of reducing the income rise disregard for tax credits.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","28529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455226","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>As announced in the combined Autumn Statement and Spending Review, the amount by which a tax credit claimant’s income can increase within the year before their tax credit award is adjusted (the income rise disregard), will be reduced from £5,000 to £2,500. The reduction to the income rise disregard will stop one family receiving a higher tax credit award over another family with precisely the same income and the same circumstances, which makes the system fairer. The household income of families before it rises will inform how they might be effected by a reduction in the income rise disregard.</p><p> </p><p>The only people who will be affected are those who will see an income increase of more than £2,500 in-year.</p><p> </p><p>Due to the way that tax credits are calculated, the amount an award will be adjusted by – because of an increase in income – will depend upon a claimant’s individual circumstances, such as the household’s income before it rises. No one will be a cash loser because their income will have increased. As an example, for an individual with a wage of £12,000, an income increase of £2,501 would lead to an adjustment in their tax credit award of just 41 pence. An increase of less than £2,500 would see no change at all.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","28529 ; 28580","2016-03-01T17:46:37.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455226/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455226/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 1.122 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what estimate his Department has made of the average change in tax credit award as a result of reducing the income rise disregard for tax credits.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","28530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455227","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-04","<p>As the Chancellor has said, a UK exit from the EU would be a long, costly and messy divorce. The finance Ministers and central bank governors of the G20 concluded at the weekend that a British exit would cause an economic shock not just to the UK but to Europe and the world. What people are asking for in this referendum campaign is a serious, sober and principled assessment from the Government setting out the facts. The Treasury will publish a comprehensive analysis of our membership of a reformed EU and the alternatives, including the long-term economic costs and benefits of EU membership and the risks associated with an exit before 23 June.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-04T14:27:29.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455227/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455227/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the potential effect on the economy of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","28535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455228","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>The cleaning service at HM Treasury is provided by through a service contract, let by the landlord for 1 Horse Guards Road (Exchequer Partnership). HM Treasury does not directly employ cleaners.</p><p> </p><p>However, the contracted cleaners that work within 1 Horse Guards Road are paid £9.15 per hour which will increase to £9.40 in April 2016.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-29T16:49:39.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455228/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455228/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Treasury: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the rate of pay is for cleaners in his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","28614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455229","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-04","<p>The cost of Employment Tribunals can be found within the HMCTS annual accounts published at<em>: </em>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/433948/hmcts-annual-report-accounts-2014-15.pdf.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-04T11:50:52.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455229/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455229/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Treasury: Employment Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department spent from the public purse on industrial tribunals in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455230","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-08","<p>I refer the Honourable member to the answer given my Rt Hon. friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office (26025)</p><p> </p><p>Like any employer, HM Treasury does not discuss individual personnel matters, however details on the remuneration of Special Advisers appointed in the current Government and information on the remuneration of Special Advisers during the Coalition Government are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","28565","2016-03-08T14:09:15.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455230/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455230/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Treasury: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answers of 10 February 2016 to Question 26025 and 25 February 2016 to Question 27582, whether special advisors at his Department are included within the public sector one per cent pay rise limit.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","28550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455231","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-04","<p>Since April 2011, the department has maintained a contracts database. A search of that database by the Crown Commercial Service has not identified any consultancy contracts that have been terminated early.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to April 2011, the department did not hold a central record of contracts. To attempt to extract the information from local records would be at disproportionate cost.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-04T11:54:59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455231/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455231/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Treasury: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many consultants' contracts were terminated early in each of the last six years for which figures are available; and what the cost of each such termination was in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455232","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-08","<p>I refer the Honourable member to the answer given my Rt Hon. friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office (26025)</p><p> </p><p>Like any employer, HM Treasury does not discuss individual personnel matters, however details on the remuneration of Special Advisers appointed in the current Government and information on the remuneration of Special Advisers during the Coalition Government are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","28550","2016-03-08T14:09:16.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455232/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455232/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Treasury: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether any of his Department's advisors received a pay rise of more than one per cent in the last two financial years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","28565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455233","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-04","<p>All Treasury consultations published since the department since 2010 can be found online at https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=hm-treasury&amp;publication_filter_option=consultations</p><p> </p><p>This includes the consultation’s title.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-04T11:51:58.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455233/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455233/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Treasury: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) publications, (b) consultation documents and (c) circulars his Department has issued since August 2012; and what the title was of each such publication, consultation document or circular.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455234","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-04","<p>The information requested is not available, as separate data for cases based wholly or partially on the Human Rights Act 1998 are not recorded.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-04T11:57:01.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455234/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455234/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Treasury: Human Rights Act 1998","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many civil law suits have been brought against his Department based either wholly or partially on grounds provided by the Human Rights Act 1998; how many such suits were settled out of court before a court judgment was delivered; and how much such settlements have cost the public purse since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455235","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-04","<p>The Treasury’s overtime costs are published and can be found on <a href="http://www.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.gov.uk</a></p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-04T11:59:22.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455235/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455235/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Treasury: Overtime","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department has paid to staff in overtime in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","28695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455236","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-10","<p>I refer the honourable members to the recent HMRC release.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tax-credit-statistics-on-eea-nationals" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tax-credit-statistics-on-eea-nationals</a></p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","29489 ; 29490 ; 29491 ; 29556","2016-03-10T16:19:19.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455236/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455236/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","National Insurance: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 11 January 2016 to Question 20697, on national insurance: EEA Nationals, when HM Revenue and Customs will publish the information referred to in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","28570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455237","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>Voluntary redundancy and workforce restructuring is not contingent upon access to six-figure exit payments. As such, we do not expect the cap to have a widespread impact on the take-up of voluntary redundancy, and believe the cap will enable public sector employers to retain the tools to effectively make organisational changes to their workforce whilst offering those made redundant generous provisions for loss of employment.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-01T11:28:11.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455237/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455237/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Academies: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the proposed public sector exit payments cap on the flexibility of academy chains to restructure their workforce.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","28584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455238","Department for Education","false","2016-03-01","<p>The reformed national pay and terms and conditions arrangements allow all schools considerable flexibility over the pay of their teachers.</p><p>Staff at academies are employees of academy trusts, companies limited by guarantee with charitable status. Whilst academy trusts are classified as public sector bodies, their staff are not employees of the Crown. Academies have more control over their budgets so that they can meet their school’s needs more effectively and have the flexibility to reward the best teachers and excellent performance. These are the reasons they are not included within the statutory national pay and terms and conditions arrangements, which includes the current one per cent cap on pay increases.</p><p>Many academies have pay systems that mirror the provisions of the statutory national arrangements and many converter academy staff have ‘Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) Regulations’ rights that preserve their entitlement to the national pay and terms and conditions arrangements.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","28585","2016-03-01T16:48:35.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455238/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455238/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-25","Academies: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reasons academy schools are not subject to public sector pay and terms.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","28588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455239","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>As announced in the combined Autumn Statement and Spending Review, the amount by which a tax credit claimant’s income can increase within the year before their tax credit award is adjusted (the income rise disregard), will be reduced from £5,000 to £2,500. The reduction to the income rise disregard will stop one family receiving a higher tax credit award over another family with precisely the same income and the same circumstances, which makes the system fairer. The household income of families before it rises will inform how they might be effected by a reduction in the income rise disregard.</p><p> </p><p>The only people who will be affected are those who will see an income increase of more than £2,500 in-year.</p><p> </p><p>Due to the way that tax credits are calculated, the amount an award will be adjusted by – because of an increase in income – will depend upon a claimant’s individual circumstances, such as the household’s income before it rises. No one will be a cash loser because their income will have increased. As an example, for an individual with a wage of £12,000, an income increase of £2,501 would lead to an adjustment in their tax credit award of just 41 pence. An increase of less than £2,500 would see no change at all.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","28529 ; 28530","2016-03-01T17:46:37.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455239/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455239/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-25","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Government's memorandum submitted to the Lords Secondary Legislation Committee on 28 January 2016, what the evidential basis is for the statement that there will be no cash losers from the reduction of the income rise disregards for tax credits.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","28580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455240","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-08","<p>The Department estimates that if all local authorities who deliver social care were to choose to use a two per cent precept this would total £393 million in 2016-17. If similar flexibilities were used in full in subsequent years, this would rise to around £1.8 billion in 2019-20. Local authorities will be required to provide confirmation that the additional revenue has been used for Adult Social Care in addition to confirming the amounts of expenditure in statistical returns. In addition, the Secretary of State will take account of local authorities’ actions when setting referendum principles in future years.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-03-08T16:47:32.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455240/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455240/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-25","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will estimate the maximum overall annual amount which could be raised if each local authority imposed the maximum social care levy.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","28472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455241","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-07","<p>I have carried out a wide range of domestic visits since May 2015. Transparency data is recorded on the Department's website.</p><p />","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2016-03-07T15:11:35.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455241/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455241/answer","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455241/answer/previousversion/48356","Biography information for Greg Clark","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-25","Department for Communities and Local Government: Domestic Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what official domestic visits he has made since May 2015; and what the purpose of each such visit was.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","28444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455242","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-04","<p>Guidance to staff now states that refreshments may only be ordered for meetings with external attendees of longer than four hours.</p><p>The Department has no separate budget for hospitality and catering. The Department spent £10,829.44 on hospitality from May 2015 to 29 February 2016.</p><p>This compares to a bill of almost £500,000 in the last year of the Labour Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-04T14:22:50.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455242/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455242/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455242/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/455242/answer/previousversion/48357","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-25","Department for Communities and Local Government: Official Hospitality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much his Department has spent on (a) hospitality and (b) catering since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","28445"
